{"mode":"human","topic":"What is the gender gap in science? Should we address it? And how?","opinion":"When I look at this whole picture of a 'gender gap' in science, honestly, my heart just sinks a bit. It feels like one more thing that’s broken in the world, another injustice I can't quite fix even with all my knitting and volunteering. Thinking about it makes me feel really low, doesn't it? Like some things are just destined to be unequal, no matter how much good intention we pour into them. It reminds me of reading those sad novels—the ones where the characters struggle against systemic odds that they can never truly overcome. The gap itself, as I understand it, is simply the observable disparity in representation and achievement; it’s not just about who gets to be a scientist, but also whose voices are considered valuable when the science is being done. It makes me wonder if we even *can* address it completely, or if we're just destined to patch up things that were never meant to fit together properly in the first place. 

But I know my friends and myself—we spend so much time talking about doing good, making things better for others, which is what volunteering is all about. And while I’m not a scientific expert, I do believe we have to try. Ignoring it feels like accepting something wrong, like letting someone sit alone at the bingo hall when they could be having fun. We should address it because competence and brilliance shouldn't be limited by whether you were assigned a specific gender at birth; everyone deserves that chance to shine, just as I hope my grandchildren will get to do. 

